# Forward PWAs still re-fetching the old hashed manifest URL (now gone)
# to the stable path. `_redirects` fire even when no asset matches.
# Removable in ~a month, once most installs have refreshed.
#
# Anchor the match to the `.webmanifest` extension: a bare `manifest-*`
# splat also swallows hashed route chunks like `manifest-route-<hash>.js`
# (301'd to JSON, they break the gallery's dynamic import). The `:hash`
# placeholder matches any non-`/` run — hyphenated hashes included — while
# the trailing literal keeps it scoped to the old manifest asset.
/_build/assets/manifest-:hash.webmanifest  /manifest.webmanifest  301

# Serve the flattened `/share/:endpoint` shell for every endpoint id. The id is
# a live client-side relay handle, so no per-id page can be prerendered; without
# this a cold load falls through to the 404 shell and the client hydrates a
# share route against 404 markup, throwing a hydration error. A 200 rewrite (not
# a redirect) keeps the id in the URL for the client router. `:id` matches a
# single segment — unlike a `/share/*` splat it leaves `/share/` (the index's
# own trailing-slash URL) alone. The target is the extensionless
# `/share-connect` (served from `/share-connect.html`): Cloudflare strips a
# trailing `/index` or `.html` from the target and 307s to the stripped path, so
# naming the `.html` here would bounce every id to a bare `/share-connect`,
# dropping it from the URL. Living outside `/share/` also keeps the stripped
# form from renormalizing into `/share/:id` and tripping loop detection.
/share/:id  /share-connect  200
